        "body":"<p><strong>In May this year, I bought a Ford Fiesta from the car dealer Sandicliffe in Leicester, and completed an online customer survey which promised me £50 cash back if I introduced someone who subsequently bought a car within one month.</strong></p><p><strong>Two weeks later, my partner and I returned and he bought a Mazda MX5, which he had seen at the time I bought mine. When he paid for the car I handed over the voucher and was told a cheque would be in the post. Since then I have heard nothing, despite telephone calls and visits to the showroom when my car has been in for work. Admittedly £50 is not a lot of money – not enough to fill either car with petrol – but why are we enticed with cashback offers which the company concerned has no intention of honouring? </strong><em>LT, Leicester</em></p><p>You are right to draw attention to this practice, as we receive many complaints about companies' failure to actually deliver on their promises. Finally, on 13 September you received a cheque for £50 from Sandicliffe. It had been posted on 2 September, but with just 33p postage and to the wrong address. Fortunately the occupants know you and brought it round. Although we can take no credit for the happy outcome, this shows that persistence pays off. Let's hope the company has updated its postal records and acquainted itself with current postage rates.</p><p><strong>We welcome letters but cannot answer individually. Email us at </strong><a href=\"mailto:consumer.champions@theguardian.com\" title=\"\"><strong>consumer.champions@theguardian.com</strong></a><strong> or write to Consumer Champions, Money, the Guardian, 90 York Way, London N1 9GU. Please include a daytime phone number</strong></p><!-- Guardian Watermark: internal-code/content/419508899|2013-10-16T18:19:24Z|d208e05a76d9aaa2feb1f354684e26cef4512c29 -->",
