        "trailText":"<p>Groceries didn't arrive on time at our holiday home, yet Asda still charged us the full amount of £196.51</p>",
        "headline":"Holiday meal ruined after Asda failed to deliver",
        "body":"<p><strong>Asda has taken payment on my credit card for £196.51 for an online grocery delivery I never received, and is not responding to my demands for a refund. I placed an order online with Asda for a delivery to a rented holiday house in Pembroke. The delivery was booked to coincide with our arrival for a week's holiday on 31 August between 4pm and 6pm. The delivery did not arrive within the time slot, so I rang the customer service number provided at about 6.05pm and was kept on hold for almost 25 minutes (as I only had access to a mobile I was charged £4.23 for the call). When they finally answered I was told they had experienced computer failure and that all deliveries were delayed by up to three hours. I said I could not wait that long with a tired and hungry family in a holiday home without even a teabag. So I asked if I could cancel, and the person said that was no problem. </strong></p><p><strong>We then went out for 10 minutes and while we were gone the delivery van came (this was just before 7pm). The card left by the driver stated we had to ring customer services to rearrange delivery. We decided not to try and rearrange the delivery as we had already told customer services to cancel it anyway. </strong></p><p><strong>Returning from holiday a week later I checked my credit card online and found that Asda had charged me for the shopping. I emailed to complain, but received an email suggesting that I was just moaning about a missed time slot and stating that the local store had confirmed delivery. I then sent a written complaint on 20 September demanding a refund and compensation. I got no reply and sent a further email – still no reply. Can you help? I will never consider shopping at Asda again. </strong><em>KK, York</em><strong> </strong></p><p>We have all got so used to the convenience of online grocery shopping that when it lets us down it is all the more disappointing. What seems odd about this is that you were asked to provide two mobile phone numbers when placing your order so drivers could contact you in case of any problems. After we contacted Asda, it admitted it hadn't met its own \"high standards\" of customer service and leapt into apologetic mode, refunding your credit card in full and also sending you £30 in vouchers to make up for the inconvenience.</p><p>It said: \"After investigating the issue it appears there was a system error at the store which occurred when the payment was requested from the bank, which caused the glitch. Our operations team is investigating this to make sure it doesn't happen again. We can only apologise for not resolving it sooner.\" So it looks like you WILL have to shop at Asda in order to spend the vouchers.</p><p><strong>We welcome letters but cannot answer individually. Email us at </strong><a href=\"mailto:consumer.champions@theguardian.com\" title=\"\"><strong>consumer.champions@theguardian.com</strong></a><strong> or write to Consumer Champions, Money, the Guardian, 90 York Way, London N1 9GU. Please include a daytime phone number</strong></p><!-- Guardian Watermark: internal-code/content/419507211|2013-10-16T18:19:24Z|4fac307a6ffd8838ea1ccdd8ab2011d14732e332 -->",
