        "headline":"RAC's breakdown in service left me stranded",
        "body":"<p><strong>I have been a member of the RAC for years, but had not used them until September when my car (with attached catering trailer) broke down about 10 miles from my home. I spent more than an hour trying to ring the breakdown number and was fed up listening to the recorded message. When an operator finally answered I was told someone would be with me within the hour. No one came. </strong></p><p><strong>I then had to spend another 40 minutes getting through again, only to be told it would be at least three or four hours until someone would be with me. In desperation I spent £150 to have my trailer collected (I could not leave it as it held frozen stock worth more than £1,000, which I would have lost had it defosted). I waited with my car and after speaking to the RAC again, after waiting another hour, I was told it would be another three or four hours before an RAC person would be with me. I ended up paying privately (another £50) for rescue and getting home. </strong></p><p><strong>The next day I spent more than an hour trying to reach the RAC to complain and also to get my car collected and taken to my garage. Can you help? </strong><em>CG, Ross on Wye, Herefordshire</em><strong> </strong></p><p>You were, it seems, the victim of unfortunate timing, but that is no excuse. The RAC said it was dealing with a high number of breakdowns nationally at the end of the school holidays – one of the busiest travelling periods of the summer. In a statement it said: \"As a result, CG regrettably suffered unacceptable delays, both on the phone and at the roadside. We do understand how important it is that delays such as this are prevented wherever possible and we are working hard to ensure there is no repetition.\"</p><p>It is writing to you to apologise and, as a gesture of goodwill, has offered you six months' free membership, which is worth about £50 – but not the £200 you wanted. We pressed RAC for a better offer, but none was forthcoming. You have told us you will not be taking up the offer of six months' free membership as you no longer want to be a member.</p><p><strong>We welcome letters but cannot answer individually. Email us at </strong><a href=\"mailto:consumer.champions@theguardian.com\" title=\"\"><strong>consumer.champions@theguardian.com</strong></a><strong> or write to Consumer Champions, Money, the Guardian, 90 York Way, London N1 9GU. Please include a daytime phone number</strong></p><!-- Guardian Watermark: internal-code/content/419505992|2013-10-16T18:19:24Z|1c61a830cabbd140c54d3e6acc29d9d7d757e5cf -->",
